<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06075183 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06075183 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Lonny Hurlbut, San Juan Bautista's flamboyant police chief,awaits a court appearance in February. He was released from jail Wednesday.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PAST; SAN-JUAN-BAUTISTA; POLICE; OFFICIAL; SAN-BENITO; JAIL; END  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Former San Juan Bautista Police Chief Lonny Greywolf Hurlbut has been releasedfrom San Benito County jail after serving a little more than four months of aone-year sentence for conspiracy and evidence tampering.;    Hurlbut, whoentered jail Nov. 7, was released just after noon Wednesday to participate inan electronic monitoring program, according to Stan Peterlin, deputy chiefprobation officer.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EX-POLICE CHIEF LEAVES JAIL AFTER 4 MONTHS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The colorful ex-cop, who may have brought as much attention to San JuanBautista as its famed mission, antique stores and first-class restaurants,left jail without talking to the news media. He could not be reached forcomment Thursday.;    Hurlbut, 55, must wear a device on his ankle that willallow probation officials to know where he is 24 hours a day, Peterlin said.About 20 people wear such a monitor in San Benito County, where electronicmonitoring began about a year ago, he said.;    Hurlbut's release came a dayafter he was denied early release by San Benito County Superior Court JudgeThomas Breen. Breen sentenced Hurlbut to jail in October, following aprobation report rejecting Hurlbut's attorney's request for probation,electronic monitoring or bail, pending appeal.;    Peterlin said Hurlbutqualified for the electronic monitoring program by having a clean jail record,a job offer and a reliable family to sponsor him. During curfew, from 6 p.m.to 6 a.m., Hurlbut's electronic monitor will alert authorities if he goes morethan 150 feet from home, Peterlin said.;    Hurlbut was convicted July 14 ontestimony that he added marijuana to an amount confiscated from a suspect inorder to have charges upgraded from a misdemeanor to a felony.;    Hurlbut isappealing the conviction and seeking a new trial though the 6th DistrictAppellate Program, a state-sponsored program for penniless defendants.;   Hired as police chief of San Juan Bautista in 1982, Hurlbut becameinternationally known because of his Old West garb and for sometimespatrolling on horseback.;    When the city, whose population of 1,570 makes itone of the tiniest in the state, couldn't afford the pay raise Hurlbut wanted,the business community chipped in to make up the difference.;    He latergained notoriety for off-duty exploits that got him in trouble with the law.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DALE RODEBAUGH, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  South County  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910315  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  392  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 15, 199100075183,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>